'''Kumano Shrine''' (熊野神社) is a shrine located in {{ill|Azumino|ja|安曇野市|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Nagano Prefecture|ja|長野県|qq=draft}}. Under the {{ill|Modern typeing System|ja|近代社格制度|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines|1=Modern system of Ranked Shinto shrines|qq=draft}}, it was classified as a {{ill|Gōsha|ja|郷社|qq=draft}}.
== Deities == The shrine enshrines the following four deities:<ref>長野県町村誌, 1876</ref> * {{ill|Izanami|ja|伊弉冊神|qq=draft}} * {{ill|Hayatama-no-Mikoto|ja|速玉男命|qq=draft}} * {{ill|Izunome-no-Mikoto|ja|泉津事解男命|qq=draft}} * {{ill|Susanoo|ja|素戔嗚尊|qq=draft}}
== History == According to shrine tradition, the shrine was first established in {{ill|Hakuchi|ja|白雉|qq=draft}} 1 (650) when {{ill|Kumano Gongen|ja|熊野権現|qq=draft}} was enshrined. It was later rebuilt in {{ill|Ōei 8|ja|応永|qq=draft}} 8 (1401) to enshrine the three Kumano deities. A temple known as Jingūji was established on the southern grounds in {{ill|Ōei 18|ja|応永18|qq=draft}} (1411) by a monk from Kumano and housed a standing statue of the Eleven-Faced Kannon.
During the {{ill|Bunroku|ja|文禄|qq=draft}} era (1592–1596), the shrine received an allotment of five koku of shrine land, Ranking it among the most significant shrines in Azumi District, alongside {{ill|Hotaka Shrine|ja|穂高神社|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Sumiyoshi Shrine|ja|住吉神社 (安曇野市)|qq=draft}}. The shrine played a pivotal role during the {{ill|Jōkyō Uprising|ja|貞享騒動|qq=draft}} in 1686 when {{ill|Tada Kasuke|ja|多田加助|qq=draft}} and his followers swore oaths of rebellion on its grounds.
In 1902, the shrine was elevated to the Rank of Gōsha. In 1907, it merged with the Yasaka Shrine of Shimonakakaya, and in 1923, it enshrined {{ill|Inari|ja|伏見稲荷|qq=draft}}.
== Ofune Matsuri == The annual {{ill|Ofune Matsuri|ja|お船祭り|1=Ofune Matsuri|qq=draft}}, held in August, features elaborate floats known as "ships" (お船) that are paraded through the area.<ref>[https://www.city.azumino.nagano.jp/site/mizumonogatari/2491.html 熊野神社のお船祭り], Azumino City</ref>
== Cultural Properties == The shrine and its associated properties have been designated as cultural assets by Azumino City: * '''Main Shrine Building''' – City Tangible Cultural Property * '''Former Yasaka Shrine Main Building''' – City Tangible Cultural Property * '''Ema (Votive Paintings)''' – City Tangible Folk Cultural Property ** Examples include depictions of flora and fauna, Yamamba and Kintarō, Shuten-dōji at Ōeyama, Susanoo slaying the Yamata-no-Orochi, warrior portraits, and the story of Tomoe Gozen. * '''Ofune Matsuri''' – City Intangible Folk Cultural Property
== location == * A11ress: 3319 Misato Akari, Azumino City, Nagano Prefecture, Japan
== References == <references/>
== Related Facilities == * {{ill|Jōkyō Gimin Memorial Hall|ja|貞享義民記念館|qq=draft}}
